<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06195019 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06195019 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CHICAGO; POLICE; OFFICIAL; SUPPORT; CHINA; CRIME; PREVENTION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  This city's police superintendent said the United States might do well to copyaspects of China's justice system, and said it might be useful to suspendconstitutional rights in some situations.;    Superintendent LeRoy Martin, whorecently returned from a visit to China, also said Nazi Germany &quot;had a verylow crime rate.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TOP CHICAGO COP PRAISES CHINA'S JUSTICE SYSTEM  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Martin said China's criminal justice system sometimes deals with crimebetter than the U.S. system.;    &quot;I know we're a democracy, but you know, Idon't think everything the communists do can't be copied,&quot; Martin said in aradio interview. &quot;And I think that there are some things they do that arebetter than what we do.&quot;;    Human rights organizations have long accusedChina of human rights abuses, particularly after its June 1989 bloodysuppression of pro-democracy demonstrators at Beijing's Tiananmen Square.Amnesty International claims that China holds hundreds of political prisonersand practices torture in its prisons.;    Martin said the U.S. Constitutionoften hampers police efforts to fight crime, and said it might be useful insome circumstances to suspend constitutional rights.;    In an interview laterwith the Chicago Tribune, when a reporter mentioned that Adolf Hitler's viewshad been popular in Nazi Germany, Martin said, &quot;And they had a very low crimerate then.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Chicago  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910713  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  208  